explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro is invoked at the top of the function and may expand to code that performs a non-local return or calls an assertion/abort. Its expansion determines whether subsequent statements in the function can be reached (i.e. it can make code after it unreachable for some or all inputs).

OS_ObjectIdGetById: The result of this call controls the if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) branch. To determine reachability of the code inside that branch (including the call to OS_SelectSingle_Impl and OS_ObjectIdRelease) we need the semantics: does it always return, can it longjmp/abort, or does it sometimes return OS_SUCCESS? Its implementation (or specification) is required.

OS_SelectSingle_Impl: Called inside the guarded branch; its behavior is relevant if it can perform non-local exits (abort/longjmp/exit) which would make subsequent statements unreachable. Also needed to know whether its call can never be reached due to earlier macros/conditions.

OS_ObjectIdRelease: Called after OS_SelectSingle_Impl when OS_ObjectIdGetById returns success. If OS_ObjectIdRelease can be non-returning or if it is irrelevant because the call site is never reached, this affects reachability analysis of that statement.

OS_SUCCESS: The constant used in the conditional check controls which path is taken. Its value and relation to possible return codes from OS_ObjectIdGetById are needed to determine if the true branch is ever taken (i.e. whether the code inside the if is reachable).

OS_printf: Commonly used inside parameter-check macros or assertion handlers; if OS_CHECK_POINTER or error paths call OS_printf (or other logging that then aborts), that affects reachability. Include to inspect macro/handler chains.

UtAssert_Abort: Unit-test/assertion abort function that does not return. Many CHECK/ASSERT macros call this on failure. If OS_CHECK_POINTER or related infrastructure calls UtAssert_Abort, that makes subsequent code unreachable in the failure case (and could make code effectively unreachable depending on macro behavior).

OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT and OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM: Constants passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById. Knowing their definitions may be necessary to understand any compile-time behavior or macro expansions that could affect reachability (for example, if macros are conditionally compiled based on these constants).

osal_id_t and OS_object_token_t: The typedefs of the function parameters/local token are needed to understand whether OS_CHECK_POINTER or other macros operate on them in a way that could change control flow (e.g. if token is a struct with destructor-like semantics via macros) and to fully inspect types used in macro expansions.

Note: The goal is to see if any statement in OS_SelectSingle can never be reached for any possible program execution; therefore any symbol that can introduce a non-local exit (macros like OS_CHECK_POINTER, assertion/abort functions) or that controls the conditional (OS_ObjectIdGetById and OS_SUCCESS) or that is the callee of the guarded code (OS_SelectSingle_Impl, OS_ObjectIdRelease) must be examined.
